content.description: The first route with bolts when walking left. Climb past two bolts on thin moves. Follow easier terrain to the top.
Move like a shaman as you highstep and dance back & forth across the blunt arete several times on the way to the top.  Don't blow the crux clip, or the shaman might rip your heart out.
content.protection: Large cams to 3" and a fixed knifeblade.
content.location: Just right of the route "The Arete" is a triangular face with a beech tree growing just to the right of center, near the wall.  This route starts and ends just to the right of the tree, and follows the blunt arete that describes the right side of the face.

content.description: The only crack line around. Climb the short but fun crack to the top placing gear along the way.

climbs.name: Killing Time in the Crystal City

content.description: The face between "Cowboys From Hell" and "Daddy's Day Out."  Begin immediately left of a beech tree, and climb straight up, then slightly left past a huge natural thread and a crystal filled pocket that gives the route it's name.  Really fun moves with a couple distinct mini cruxes.
content.protection: Perfect protection just where you need it with Tricams to size 2 and a natural thread.
content.location: Just left of Daddy's Day Out is a line of pockets and intermittent dike steps.  The route is about 10' to the right of Cowboys From Hell.

content.description: Start 15 to the left of Flakes and Dykes at a large left facing flake. Climb the flake until it ends and continue up the slab to the top.
content.location: Left Side of the Left End

content.description: Start 12 left of Cowboys. Climb a nice dike past two bolts. The climbing eases up as you finish to the trees above.
Start 10 Left of the previous route at a faint dike. Climb the faint dike up and left to a flake. Continue straight up the face to the top. A couple pieces of gear protect the route.
Start 10 left of Daddys Day Out below another bolt line. Climb up the technical face past two bolts and finish up easier terrain to the trees at the top.
Climb the arête feature just to the right of Mollys Crack.  Place gear when possible on the way.

pathTokens: New Durham Area  (Longstack, Devil's Den, Rines Hill, etc.)

content.description: The Left End is a bit short, but also has a handful of routes worth doing. The wall is about 30-35 feet at its highest. The wall keeps going left for a while and could offer many new boulder problems.
